s and animal rights activists, parents and toddlers, and the other human primates that make up the zoo's social world. He shows that in a major shift away from their unfortunate pasts, American zoos today emphasize naturalistic exhibits teeming with lush and immersive landscapes, breeding programs for endangered animals, and enrichment activities for their captive creatures. In doing so, zoos blur the imaginary boundaries we regularly use to separate culture from nature, humans from animals, and civilization from the wild. At the same time, zoos manage a wilderness of competing priorities—animal care, education, scientific research, and recreation—all while attempting to serve as centers for conservation in the wake of the current environmental and climate-change crisis. The world of the zoo reflects how we project our own prejudices and desires onto the animal kingdom, and invest nature with meaning and sentiment.A revealing portrayal of comic animals, delighted children, and feisty zookeepers, American Zoo is a remarkable close-up exploration of a classic cultural attraction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAnimal welfarezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aCaptive wild animalsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aWildlife conservationxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aZoo animalsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aZoosxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aZooszUnited StatesxEmployees. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAdventure Aquarium.  aAmericans.  aAmusement park.  aAnimal rights.  aAnimal show.  aAnimal welfare.  aArizona-Sonora Desert Museum.  aArthropod.  aAssociation of Zoos and Aquariums.  aAviary.  aBehavioral enrichment.  aBig cat.  aBiodiversity loss.  aBiodi